No attempt has been made to give all the variant readings in all the MSS. collated. Even the best of MSS. often differ from the text in places where the dem'ded agreement of the other MSS. proves the text to be eor- rect. The recording of all the variant readings of all the MSS. used would make an unweildy mass of immaterial facts as unnecessary ss it is undesir- able. It was shown in the first volume that with some few exceptions, which are aelf-evident, only those variant readings which represent groups of MSS. or text traditions are important in determining Braaeton's text. This being so, and because the actual reading of any single tradition is seldom in doubt, it seemed only necessary in most places to give merely those variants which have the authority of the group behind them. Without the curb of this limitation the references made to the MSSâ now more than twenty-three thousand in number, would have been at least doubled.
